# 1️⃣ Concept Teaching (Strict, Clear, GATE-Oriented)

---

# 🔹 What is I/O Organization?

I/O Organization deals with:

👉 Communication between:

* CPU
* Memory
* Input/Output devices

Examples:

* Keyboard
* Mouse
* Printer
* Disk

---

# 🔹 Why I/O Management is Needed?

I/O devices are:

* Much slower than CPU
* Different in speed & format

So coordination is required.

---

# 🔹 I/O Interface

Acts as bridge between CPU and devices.

Functions:

* Data transfer
* Control signals
* Status reporting

---

# 🔹 Types of I/O Transfer

---

## 1️⃣ Programmed I/O

CPU continuously checks device status.

👉 CPU busy waiting occurs.

📌 Simple but inefficient.

---

## 2️⃣ Interrupt-Driven I/O

Device interrupts CPU when ready.

👉 CPU can do other work meanwhile.

📌 Better than programmed I/O.

---

## 3️⃣ DMA (Direct Memory Access) (VERY IMPORTANT)

DMA controller transfers data directly:

[
\text{I/O Device} \leftrightarrow \text{Memory}
]

without CPU involvement.

📌 CPU only initiates transfer.

---

# 🔹 Interrupts (VERY IMPORTANT)

Interrupt = signal requesting CPU attention.

---

## 🔹 Types of Interrupts

### 1️⃣ Hardware Interrupt

Generated by hardware devices.

### 2️⃣ Software Interrupt

Generated by program/instruction.

---

## 🔹 Interrupt Handling Steps

1️⃣ Finish current instruction
2️⃣ Save state
3️⃣ Execute ISR (Interrupt Service Routine)
4️⃣ Restore state
5️⃣ Resume execution

---

# 🔹 Interrupt Priority

If multiple interrupts occur:

👉 Higher priority served first.

---

# 🔹 Polling vs Interrupt

| Polling                      | Interrupt           |
| ---------------------------- | ------------------- |
| CPU checks device repeatedly | Device notifies CPU |
| Wasteful                     | Efficient           |
| Busy waiting                 | Better utilization  |

📌 Common comparison question.

---

# 🔹 DMA Transfer Modes

---

## 1️⃣ Burst Mode

DMA transfers entire block.

## 2️⃣ Cycle Stealing

DMA takes bus one cycle at a time.

---

# 🔹 Bus Structure

Bus = communication path.

Types:

* Data bus
* Address bus
* Control bus

---

# 🔹 Common GATE Traps

* Confusing polling and interrupts
* Forgetting DMA bypasses CPU
* Mixing interrupt types

